"SECTION6_PARAGRAPH1" = "If your VO₂ max is in the low range and you’re considering a big change in your exercise routine, you may want to discuss it with your doctor first—especially if you think an underlying condition could be the cause.";
"SECTION6_PARAGRAPH2" = "Significant changes in any vital sign can indicate a change in your overall health that’s worth bringing up with your doctor.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "Cardio fitness, or cardiorespiratory fitness, is your body’s ability to take in, circulate, and use oxygen. This process relies on vital parts of the body—your heart, lungs, muscles, as well as the blood and blood vessels that connect them. This makes your cardio fitness level an excellent indicator of your overall fitness.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH2" = "To measure cardio fitness, scientists developed a metric called VO₂ max. This represents the maximum amount of oxygen your body can use during exercise. The higher your VO₂ max, the more efficient the system, and the more fit you are. So understanding VO₂ max is useful for everyone—whether you’re an elite athlete, getting in shape, or managing an illness.";
