"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH1" = "A precise measurement of VO₂ max requires specialized equipment and strenuous exercises in a lab or gym. But you can get a predicted VO₂ max using heart rate and motion data from a fitness tracker. For instance, Apple Watch can record your predicted VO₂ max after a few minutes of walking, running, or hiking.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH1" = "Cardio fitness can be an important predictor of your long-term health. There’s a link between low cardio fitness and a risk of significant health issues down the road. Wherever your cardio fitness level is now, the higher you can safely get it, the better.";
"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH1" = "Aerobic exercise that raises your heart rate and gets you breathing hard gives you the biggest boost. Workouts such as running, cycling, or high-intensity interval training are great. Even just adding a few hills to your daily walk can be a good place to start.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH3_LEARN_MORE" = "Learn more about blood oxygen";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH2" = "VO₂ max predictions are heavily dependent on your age and sex. They can also be affected by certain prescription heart medications.";
"SECTION4_HEADER" = "Why You Should Be Concerned If You’re Low";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH3" = "VO₂ max should not be confused with SpO₂, which measures a different aspect of your health—the amount of oxygen in your blood.";
